title: Grateful Dead Live at Charlotte Coliseum on 1984-10-05
description:
Set 1

Bertha-> Promised Land, West L.A. Fadeaway, Little Red Rooster, Dupree's Diamond Blues, My Brother Esau, Brown Eyed Women, Feel Like A Stranger, Might As Well

Set 2

China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> The Other One-> Black Peter-> Sugar Magnolia-> Johnny B. Goode, E: It's All Over Now Baby Blue

reviews.review_text: - Started off good, but bad second set. I hate it when they played Eyes faster than they could play. Some people like fast playing no matter how sloppy it is. I hate sloppy playing no matter how fast it is.

Speedway Boogie! There was a stock car or Nascar event in Charlotte this weekend if I remember correctly...trippin hard on musical notes, super balmy October night, Bertha/Promised/West LA were great. This matrix, however, is the real star here. Amazing quality!  Stranger w/ the lapse in verses was really kinda awesome and Phil comes through beautifully here!!

Great Show Great Tour I think this show rocks from beginning to end. Start of the 84 east coast Fall tour & I like fast/tight playing. It's why I like 82-84 so much. Find it funny when people complain/comment on Garcia's appearance/playing/personal drug habits in 1984 as music is not a modeling gig, it's about the sound & I love 82-84 for the sound and extended jams they did, especially in 83!
Pretty Darn Good Show! my hometown show. better than I remembered listening to the recording..
Estimated Brent takes the bridge jam into another dimension. Not the best I've heard, but pretty unique. Very energetic show throughout.

Road Trip Fall '84 - Day 1 Excellent Matrix Left fallowed corn and soybean fields of central Illinois for day 1 of the Grateful Dead Fall '84 tour. The '77 Dodge Aspen station wagons drove smoothly via highway 441, meandering Great Smoky Mountains National Park towards Charlotte, NC. Arrived shortly before the show started. Met friends in the parking lot, was motioned to "follow me" into the Coliseum (I didn't have a ticket). Inside, navigated towards the stage, in front of Jerry Garcia. My friend looked up, bowed his head, like wise Jerry too towards us. Next the band ripped into 'Bertha' > 'Promised Land'. Later on 'Johnny B. Goode' echoed to end the 2nd set (set list, two Chuck Berry songs). Outside the Coliseum grounds, two deadheads in crouched position called for a 'Morning Dew' encore. Not tonight, as sounds of Bob Dylan's, 'It's All Over Now, Baby Blue' wafted through the open doors.
